    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for the house i'm buying in toronto. i've never heard of that before... what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of real estate, is a trust account where a third-party holds funds until certain conditions are met. It's a common practice in Toronto, and it's actually quite similar to how a school of fish works together to protect their young - each fish is like a separate account, but they all work together to ensure the safety of the whole school. In escrow, the funds are held until the sale is complete, and then they're released to the buyer and seller as agreed upon in the contract.\n\nThink of it like a little \"goblin's nest\" where the funds are kept safe until the deal is done. The realtor is essentially acting as the \"goblin guardian\" of the funds, making sure everything goes smoothly and according to plan. The escrow account is usually set up by the lender, and it's a way to ensure that the funds are held until the sale is complete, and any conditions or contingencies are met.\n\nIn Toronto, it's common for the escrow account to be held at a title company or a trust company, and it's usually managed by a professional escrow agent. They'll handle the day-to-day operations of the account, and make sure that the funds are",
      "source": "target",
